body:
that failure message can be a bit misleading.
it's saying it's not able to load onnxruntime_providers_openvino.dll ,but it doesn't mean that dll doesn't exist at that location. the load failure can happen for a number of reasons. probably the one here is a missing dependency. can you use dependency walker to confirm the dependencies of onnxruntime_providers_openvino.dll can be found?

**Description**: 
Fix a bug for Openvino Python binding

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
Resolve #9122

body:
@snnn Thanks for the fix. Now, I see the build goes through successfully with python bindings enabled (--build_wheel) for Debug Mode using the latest master for OpenVINO-EP.

However, when I try to run any cpp or python application, it still gives me the same error.
`[E:onnxruntime:Default, provider_bridge_ort.cc:944 onnxruntime::ProviderLibrary::Get] LoadLibrary failed with error 126 "The specified module could not be found." when trying to load "C:\Users\Intel\Downloads\maajid\intel_onnxrt_cpu_fp32_ov_2021.4.58_binary_sep16\onnxruntime\build\Windows\Debug\Debug\onnxruntime_providers_openvino.dll"`

@jywu-msft Hi george, I tried getting the dependencies of the onnxruntime_providers_openvino.dll shared library.

![onnxrt_debug_build_after_fix](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29036417/134158163-5fb7a827-e26e-4d45-b6f4-83b3e6e91a84.JPG)

It is able to locate and find the path of all of its dependencies as seen from the image above.


Also attaching the similar output using dumpbin from Visual Studio tools: 

![onnrt_dumpbin_output1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29036417/134159286-b1b2da0c-64c8-42de-b7ee-857c6cc282d3.JPG)

To identify the problem:
1. Install [windbg](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/debugger/debugger-download-tools)
2.  Find the gflags.exe in the windbg install folder and start it, 

3. Select the image file tab
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/856316/74082914-91d96900-4a13-11ea-95eb-d73db8a5cf13.png)

4. Type python.exe then press the "tab" key, check "Show loader snaps" box

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/856316/74082958-b7667280-4a13-11ea-9eaf-6752695b4904.png)

5.  Start windbg, run python.exe with arguments of "test.py" (which is your test script)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/856316/74083043-7d49a080-4a14-11ea-90fa-2960544a3dce.png)

6. in the command windows, type "g", then press the enter key
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/856316/74083078-d285b200-4a14-11ea-9df4-e86c421c5617.png)

7. You'll see a lot of outputs in the debugging windows.  Please search the lines that have "LdrpProcessWork - ERROR: Unable to load DLL", and put the result here.
e.g.
 "cublas64_100.dll", Parent Module: "C:\intelpython3\lib\site-packages\onnxruntime\capi\onnxruntime_pybind11_state.pyd", Status: 0xc0000135


Please post the log here if you can't find the problematic DLL by yourself.

@snnn I think we should revert these changes from the PR: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9130

This fix has introduced regression for python API in OpenVINO-EP.

The python API for OpenVINO-EP has this feature for dynamic device_type selection during runtime which allows the users to change the device_type during the run time.

since from the change in the PR mentioned above, the global variables config are being reset before calling the CreateProvider() method, which is clearing the device_id config set by the user to default build type.

Meaning, the python-API will always pick the device_type that was used during build time rather than changing the device_type during the run time.

Also this commit was made part of onnxrt v1.9.0 Release. I know onnxrt v1.9.0 is out few hours back, but is there any way you can revert this change and cherry pick the fix commit to v1.9.0?

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/commit/45fa0daf4acb73ed5a6f343a0c1d3005b49bfd75 would fix it right?
let's fix it in master first and then later cherry pick into 1.9 branch?

> @snnn I think we should revert these changes from the PR: #9130
